First read this post:

https://stackoverflow.com/questions/20691933/how-do-i-interrupt-a-thread-given-a-future-object/62439075#62439075


The main thing you need to make sure of is that your threads **act responsibly** when the thread is interrupted.


In other words, your code&#39;s responsibility is to be ready for any interruptions. I&#39;d go so far to say that whenever you have a long running task, that you insert some interrupt ready code like this:

```java
while (... something long...) {

     ... do something long

     if (Thread.interrupted()) {
         ... stop doing what I&#39;m doing...
     }
}
```

If your code checks for `Thread.interrupted` frequently and if it handles InterruptedExceptions correctly (ie. it stops the thread loop) like this:

```
private void someMethodDeepDown() {
    while (.. long running task .. ) {
          try {
              ... do lots of work ...
    
          // or just let it propagate up!
          } catch (InterruptedException e) {
             // oh no! an interrupt! 
             Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
             throw new StopTheThreadRuntimeException(...);
          }
     }
}
```

Then that will make your threads interruptible. And then it&#39;s just a matter of tracking each thread, and when it exceeds its allotted time you can call Thread.interrupt() and it will die.

**Big Caveat**

Unfortunately, there are many libraries that don&#39;t handle InterruptedException correctly, by just suppressing it, or not checking for Thread.interrupted() in long running tasks. 

So there&#39;s no guarantee your thread will die quickly unless you have full control of the thread&#39;s code.

If you have a basic task, this might be a pattern you can adapt and apply to a _[ScheduledExecutorService](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/util/concurrent/ScheduledExecutorService.html)_.

For a comprehensive tutorial on concurrency, see the following.  
[Lesson: Concurrency (The Java&amp;trade; Tutorials &amp;gt; Essential Java Classes)](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/essential/concurrency/index.html)

It involves a parent thread that will interrupt its sub-thread after a specified amount of time.

You can use the _[Thread#join](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Thread.html#join(long))_ method to have the calling thread wait a specified amount of time before continuing its execution.

Consider the following class, _ThreadA_.  
For demonstration purposes, I&#39;m going to use _Thread#sleep_ to simulate some sort of computation.

```java
class ThreadA extends Thread {
    @Override
    public void run() {
        try {
            Thread.sleep(2000);
            System.out.println(&quot;thread-A completed&quot;);
        } catch (InterruptedException exception) {
            System.out.println(&quot;thread-A interrupted&quot;);
        }
    }
}
```

In total, _ThreadA_ is going to take 2 seconds to complete, printing _&quot;thread-A completed&quot;_ to the standard-out.

From our parent thread, we can instantiate this thread, and have the parent thread wait for a specified amount of time before continuing.

We&#39;ll start the thread by calling the _[Thread#start](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Thread.html#start())_ method.  
Additionally, we&#39;ll call _Thread#join_ and specify the amount of time to wait before returning, in this case _1,000_ milliseconds.  
Finally, upon return, we&#39;ll make a call to _[Thread#interrupt](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Thread.html#interrupt())_, notifying the thread to terminate its execution.

```java
ThreadA threadA = new ThreadA();
threadA.start();
threadA.join(1000);
threadA.interrupt();
System.out.println(&quot;parent thread completed&quot;);
```

Output

```none
parent thread completed
thread-A interrupted
```

As an example, if we increased our _join_ time to _2,500_, we&#39;ll get the following.

```none
thread-A completed
parent thread completed
```

