import java.util.Scanner;

public class BattleshipGame {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.print(&quot;Enter X and Y coordinates (e.g., 5 6): &quot;);

        // Read the input as a single line
        String input = scanner.nextLine();

        // Split the input using a space as a separator
        String[] coordinates = input.split(&quot; &quot;);

        // Extract the X and Y coordinates from the array
        int x = Integer.parseInt(coordinates[0]);
        int y = Integer.parseInt(coordinates[1]);

        // Use the extracted coordinates in your game logic
        System.out.println(&quot;X coordinate: &quot; + x);
        System.out.println(&quot;Y coordinate: &quot; + y);

        // Close the scanner
        scanner.close();
    }
}

```

As long as you type in two at at time you can just call `nextInt()` twice.  No need to mess with strings or parsing.  Type a negative number for `X` to stop input. It doesn&#39;t make sense to enter them in a `&quot;2D&quot;` array without knowing more about the array and how it is being used.  Once both values are entered, you can put them in a `&quot;1D&quot;`array using `int[] coords = {x,y};`
```
Scanner input = new Scanner(System.in);
while (true) {
    System.out.println(&quot;Please enter next X and Y: &quot;);
    int x = input.nextInt();
    if (x &lt; 0) {
        break;
    }
    int y = input.nextInt();
    System.out.println(&quot;X = &quot; x + &quot; Y = &quot; + y);
}
```
